div.p:
THIS VOLUME IS DEDICATED
TO ONE MAN,
AND HE, MY FRIEND:
WHO, BY WORD AND DEED, STOOD BY ME EVER;
WITH HIS FORTUNE RELIEVING TO THE LAST;
NEVER, EVEN IN THE DARKEST HOUR, DESERTING;
NOR, WITH A CLOUD UPON HIS BROW, OPPRESSING ME;
WHOSE FORETHOUGHT WAS ALWAYS CLEAR,
WHOSE COUNSEL SAFE;
I NAME HIM NOT, 'T WERE NEEDLESS, AND IT MIGHT OFFEND.
YET, READER, EVEN HERE IS THE
NAME WELL SPELLED FULL THRICE BEFORE THINE EYE,
AND STILL BY THEE UNSEEN!
SO TAKE THE BANDAGE OFF, AND
ROMANCE ENDS IN TRUTH.

"It's all in the Maggazene.*
                   I see'd it there, and Johnnie told me; and you can read it for yourself;
                   I'm busy now," and Hobbie continued his scrawls.

"If there was danger, we should certainly insist on your acceptance of a guard
                  from our brave young band. As it is, we shall content ourselves with the offer,
                  and your polite declinative."

the party of ladies at length passed on, tripping away as gayly as at the first;
                  and now, bounding and shouting, our lads rushed along the path by which the others
                  came to the summit rock.

"Well," says Amos; "I tell you what S——, you shall ride on my back all round the
                  seminary to-morrow; and I'll climb the old liberty-pole with you on my shoulders;
                  and we'll eat the oranges, won't we, up at the cross-tree?"
